Thoracic adhesive apparatus present, consisting of ridges of skin (striae) in oblong field extending from isthmus to level of middle of pectoral-fin base, with narrow elliptic median depression on posterior half almost enclosed posteriorly by skin ridges (
Fig. 2
); its width 55.8–72.1 % of its length. Striae uninterrupted; medial striae orientated anteriorly, lateral ones anterolaterally.

Distribution. Known from the Mausam, Sur Luite (both tributaries of the Tuivai River), Tlawng and Tuirial rivers in Mizoram, northeastern India (
Fig. 3
). The Tlawng, Tuirial and Tuivai rivers form part of the Barak River drainage, which is itself part of the Surma-Meghna River system.
